<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-692-259  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 692 259.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Russian language tools reviews available. (reviews are fromComputerPress and from PC World USSR)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MagazinesSoviet UnionSoftware PublishersLanguage TranslationPC World USSR (Periodical)ComputerPress (Periodical)Russian Language.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>RUSSIAN LANGUAGE TOOLS REVIEWS AVAILABLE 12/03/90 MOSCOW, U.S.S.R., 1990 DEC3 (NB) -- Two Moscow computer magazines have published reviews of Russianlanguage-specific products -- resident dictionaries and spellcheckers.andM;The 8th issue of ComputerPress has an article about five Russian-madememory-resident English to Russian and Russian to English dictionaries.andP;  Themagazine has found that among these products, ranging in price from 480 to2000 roubles, a program called Lingvo, product of Moscow-based &quot;Bit&quot;enterprise is the best in its class due to its fast speed, excellent userinterface, and the simplicity of adding new words to its wide rangingdictionaries.andM;PC World USSR (issue number 5), in its survey of five spellcheckers developedin the USSR found that &quot;there was no product substantially better than theothers&quot; in this category and recommended perspective buyers wait until early1991 when new versions of some of these packages, with current bugs fixed,are expected  to be released.andP;  There was no &quot;Excellent&quot; mark given in thetesting tables and the article reports some major problems with each of thesoftware packages tested.andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19901201)</TEXT></DOC>